## Recall Aristotle and the first figure

Recall [Aristotle's first figure](https://carnap.io/shared/walsh@g.ucla.edu/book-pred-aristotelian.pandoc#the-first-figure), where we have chosen the letters so as to better match with Euler's diagrams:

<table style="width:120%">
  <tr>
    <th>Name</th>
    <th>Valid argument</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Barbara</td>
    <td>All C are A, All A are B $\vdash$ All C are B</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Celarent</td>
    <td>No B are C, All A are B $\vdash$ No A are C</td>
  <tr>
    <td>Darii</td>
    <td>All A are B, Some C are A $\vdash$ Some C are B</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Ferio</td>
    <td>No A are B, Some C are A $\vdash$ Some C are not B</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<br>

Today we are going to look at diagrammatic representations of these arguments, as it historically developed.[^8] Diagrams were not part of Aristotle's procedure: recall he simply enumerates these four paradigmatic valid arguments and gives natural language examples that are suggestive of their validity. However, diagrams are often helpful in elucidating complex arguments and in producing counterexamples which demonstrate invalidity.

[^8]: For the history of this subject, see: [Bennett, Deborah. 2015. “Origins of the Venn Diagram.” In Research in History and Philosophy of Mathematics, 105–19. Springer International Publishing](https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Bennett%202015%20-%20Origins%20of%20the%20Venn%20Diagram.pdf).

