## Euler diagrams and invalidity

Euler also used these diagrams to show invalidity:

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> *Example of invalid argument 1*: Some A are B, No B are C $\nvdash$ Some C are not A  </p>

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Euler%201802%20-%20Letters%20of%20Euler%20to%20a%20German%20Princess,%20Plate%20I%20Figure%2024%20Invalid%201.png
" alt="Euler diagram to show invalidity" width="300"/>

This shows the invalidity because the premises are true in the diagram but the conclusion is false. For, some A are B, as shown by the fact that the shapes overlap. And No B are C as shown by the fact that the B,C shapes do no overlap. And yet the conclusion is false in the model, since all C in the small inner circle to the left are A, and hence *no* C are not A.[^2]

Here is a another simple example of invalidity:

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> *Example of invalid argument 2*: All A are B, Some B are C $\nvdash$ Some A are C  </p>

One can show the invalidity of this using the following Euler diagram:

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Euler%201802%20-%20Letters%20of%20Euler%20to%20a%20German%20Princess,%20Plate%20I%20Figure%2013%20Invalid%202.png" alt="Euler diagram to show invalidity" width="300"/>

This diagram shows the argument to be invalid since the premises are true but the conclusion is false in the diagram. For, "All A are B" is true since the A shape is entirely contained within the B shape. And "Some B are C" is true since the B shape and the C shape overlap. But "Some A are C" is false since the A shape and the C shape do not overlap.


[^2]: This last step from "All C are A" to "No C are not A" is an instance of third conversion.


