## Leibniz and linear diagrams

Euler recognized that for his purposes one could be drawing squares as opposed to circles. In an unpublished manuscript from about a century earlier, Leibniz noted that one could do the same thing with line segments.[^3]

[^3]: [Leibniz, Gottfried Wilhelm. 1903. “De Formae Logicae Comprobatione per Linearum Ductus.” In Opuscules et Fragments Inedits de Leibniz Phil., VII, B, IV, 1–10., edited by Louis Couturat, 292–331](https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Leibniz%201903%20-%20De%20formae%20logicae%20comprobatione%20per%20linearum%20ductus.pdf)


Here is Leibniz's diagram of Barbara, where to the very left the three properties are represented with circles like in Euler diagrams but in the center the three properties are represented with line segments:

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; *Barbara*: All C are A, All A are B $\vdash$ All C are B.

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Leibniz%201903%20-%20De%20formae%20logicae%20comprobatione%20per%20linearum%20ductus%20Barbara.png" alt="Leibniz's diagram of Barbara" width="600"/>

(The word "Omne" is Latin for "all" and the word "est" is Latin for "is").

Now, in Euler diagrams the convention was that "All C are A" meant that the C shape was entirely contained within the A shape. In Leibniz's linear representation, the idea is as indicated in the below video:

<video controls width="500" src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/vid/prop-euler-venn-leibniz-line.mp4"/> </video>

<br>

That is, in Leibniz's diagram, one is supposed to think of the line segments as all being parts of one and the same line which is obtained by vertically shifting them all to one and the same line. With that convention in place, the other syllogisms in the first figure can likewise be understood in terms of these linear diagrams:

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; *Celarent*: No B are C, All A are B $\vdash$ No A are C.

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Leibniz%201903%20-%20De%20formae%20logicae%20comprobatione%20per%20linearum%20ductus%20Celerant.png" alt="Leibniz's diagram of Celarent" width="600"/>

(You can probably guess, but "Nullum" gets translated from the Latin as "no" here in Celarent, and "Quoddam" gets translated from the Latin as "some" below in Darii).

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; *Darii*: All A are B, Some C are A $\vdash$ Some C are B.

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Leibniz%201903%20-%20De%20formae%20logicae%20comprobatione%20per%20linearum%20ductus%20Darii.png" alt="Leibniz's diagram of Darii" width="600"/>

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; *Ferio*: No A are B, Some C are A $\vdash$ Some C are not B

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Leibniz%201903%20-%20De%20formae%20logicae%20comprobatione%20per%20linearum%20ductus%20Ferio.png" alt="Leibniz's diagram of Ferio" width="600"/>

What about the invalid arguments we went over in the previous section? One could easily describe this using these linear diagrams:

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> *Example of invalid argument 1*:  Some A are B, No B are C $\nvdash$ Some C are not A  </p>

<video controls width="700" src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/vid/prop-euler-venn-leibniz-invalidity1.mp4"/> </video>

<br>

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> *Example of invalid argument 2*: All A are B, Some B are C $\nvdash$ Some A are C  </p>

