## Set theory and diagrams

Last time we went over [sets](https://carnap.io/shared/walsh@g.ucla.edu/book-pred-sets.pandoc), and all the diagrams we presented up above can be naturally described as sets. The easiest to set-theoretically represent would be the linear examples from Leibniz. For, we can describe all the lines as small subsets of the natural numbers, which carries a natural linear structure.

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> *Example of invalid argument 1*:  Some A are B, No B are C $\nvdash$ Some C are not A

To show the invalidity of this using sets, one lets A, B, C be small subsets of natural numbers which bear the containment relationships of the diagram we drew up above.

<video controls width="700" src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/vid/prop-euler-venn-leibniz-invalidity1-numbers.mp4"/> </video>

<br>

As the video suggests, we could define the following sets just by viewing A,B,C in the diagram up above as parts of the the natural number line up to the number 10:

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $B = \{x\in \mathbb{N}: 0\leq x \leq 6\}$  </p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $A = \{x\in \mathbb{N}: 3\leq x \leq 10\}$  </p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $C = \{x\in \mathbb{N}: 8\leq x \leq 10\}$  </p>

Then one can check that Some A are B (such as $x=3,4,5,6$) and No B are C (since B ends at 6 and C only starts at 8), and yet it is false that Some C are not A, since all the C are are in A.

Some other choices of numbers would have worked just as well. For instance, we could have replaced 3 by 2, and we could have replaced 8 by 9. But not all choices of numbers would have worked to demonstrate the invalidity of this argument. For instance, we could not have replaced 8 by 2, since this would have made "Some C are not A" be true, namely $x=2$.

<br>

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> *Example of invalid argument 2*: All A are B, Some B are C $\nvdash$ Some A are C  </p>

To show the invalidity of this using sets, we could do the same thing with the second diagram we drew up above.

<video controls width="700" src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/vid/prop-euler-venn-leibniz-invalidity2-numbers.mp4"/> </video>

<br>

As indicated, we can then define the following sets:

<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $A = \{x\in \mathbb{N}: 0\leq x \leq 40\}$  </p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $B = \{x\in \mathbb{N}: 0\leq x \leq 50\}$  </p>
<p style="margin-left: 40px"> $C = \{x\in \mathbb{N}: 45\leq x \leq 47\}$  </p>

One can then check that All A are B since any number between zero and 40 is also between 0 and 50. And Some B are C since the numbers $x=45,46,47$ are both B and C. However, it is not the case that "Some A are C" is true since this would require that there be some overlap between A and C, while A stops at 45 and C starts at 45.

These number-theoretic examples are useful because they are simple to describe and because they can be easily mechanically checked for correctness since numbers are easy to computationally implement.

