## Set theory and diagrams and connectives

There are some general principles connecting diagrams and sets and connectives that were implicit in what we just did:

<table style="width:120%">
  <tr>
    <th>Proposition</th>
    <th>Diagrammatic Correlate</th>
    <th>Set-theoretic Correlate</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>All F are G</td>
    <td>F is entirely contained in G</td>
    <td>$F\subseteq G$</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Some F are G</td>
    <td>F and G overlap</td>
    <td>$F\cap G\neq \emptyset$</td>
  <tr>
    <td>Some F are not G</td>
    <td>F overlaps with some part outside of G</td>
    <td>$F\setminus G\neq \emptyset$</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>No F are G</td>
    <td>There is no overlap between F and G</td>
    <td>$F\cap G=\emptyset$</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<br>

In the last column we introduce some set-theoretic notation related to the propositional connectives:


<table style="width:120%">
  <tr>
    <th>Name</th>
    <th>Symbol</th>
    <th>Definition</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Intersection of $X,Y$</td>
    <td>$X\cap Y$</td>
    <td>$X\cap Y= \{x: x\in X \wedge x\in Y\}$</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Union of $X,Y$</td>
    <td>$X\cup Y$</td>
    <td>$X\cup Y= \{x: x\in X \vee x\in Y\}$</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Difference of $X$ from $Y$</td>
    <td>$X\setminus Y$</td>
    <td>$X\setminus Y = \{x: x\in X \wedge x\notin Y\}$</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<br>

(The union operation was not deployed today, but it is a natural companion to the other two). To illustrate all this, consider the following Euler diagram:

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Large-Euler-Diagram.png" alt="Large Euler diagram" width="700"/>

One can check that the following are all true on this diagram:

1. Some $P_1$ are $P_2$
2. Some $P_1$ are not $Q_3$
3. All $Q_1$ are $P_1$
4. All $Q_4$ are not $P_1$
5. No $Q_4$ are $P_1$

