## Venn and concerns about diagrammatic reasoning

We have been calling the diagrams drawn today *Euler diagrams*. There are more often today called *Venn diagrams*, after a 19th Century logician Venn who did a lot of work on them. However, Venn himself was animated primarily about what he saw as a failing of Euler diagrams. He was concerned that there was no precise correspondence between Aristotelian propositions and the diagrams:[^6]

[^6]: p. 330 of: [Venn, John. 1880. “On the Forms of Logical Proposition.” Mind; a Quarterly Review of Psychology and Philosophy 5 (19): 336–49](https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Venn%201880%20-%20On%20the%20Forms%20of%20Logical%20Proposition.pdf).

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Venn%201880%20-%20On%20the%20Forms%20of%20Logical%20Proposition%20p.%20339%20part%202.png" alt="Venn quotation" width="700"/>

In (1), the idea is that A and B are the same shape, namely the displayed circle. Venn wrote of these that:

&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  <img src="https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Venn%201880%20-%20On%20the%20Forms%20of%20Logical%20Proposition%20p.%20339%20part%201.png" alt="Venn quotation" width="700"/>

Maybe the issue about (4) is not terribly important: after all, in any diagram there are going to be different features of it one could draw attention to. But the issue about (1) and (2) seems more important. If one had a premise "All A are B" then to carry out an argument one would have to consider two different diagrams, namely (1) and (2). After all, if one focused just on diagrams like (2), one might mistakenly think that "All A are B $\vdash$ Some B are not A.'' In some sense we saw this issue before, in Euler's multiple diagrams for Darii and Ferio (cf. [Euler diagrams of the first figure](#euler-diagrams-of-the-first-figure)). But Venn drew attention to this point again, and noted that if one really wanted to do entire long arguments in a digrammatic way, one would have to be paying attention to an immensely large number of different cases.

Venn's own solution to this issue was to work with a more elaborate set of diagrammatic conventions and rules that were more amenable to carrying out proofs.[^7] Time permitting, we will return to this later in the course.

[^7]: See [Venn, J. 1880. “On the Diagrammatic and Mechanical Representation of Propositions and Reasonings.” The London, Edinburgh, and Dublin Philosophical Magazine and Journal of Science 10 (59): 1–18](https://logic-teaching.github.io/pred/texts/Venn%201880%20-%20On%20the%20diagrammatic%20and%20mechanical%20representation%20of%20propositions%20and%20reasonings.pdf).

